    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Echoes of Elian; A Father's Love</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Jeff Sovern says he wonders what Elian Gonzalez controversy says about views of father's roles in raising children</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>You have reported on the effects of Elian Gonzalez's return -- on Cuba, on Miami and on the Cuban-American lobby (news articles, June 30).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>You have reported on the effects of Elian Gonzalez's return -- on Cuba, on Miami and on the Cuban-American lobby (news articles, June 30).</p>
        <p>What about the effect on father-child relationships? As a father raising two small girls alone after the death of their mother, I wonder what this controversy says about views of fathers' roles in raising children.</p>
        <p>For both my daughters and me, the most important relationship in our lives is the one we share.</p>
        <p>JEFF SOVERN  Kew Gardens, Queens  June 30, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a professor of law at St. John's University.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
